# Phenotype Construction

## Load & Reshape CSV

> **FIX (Critical — was mixing traits across genotypes):**
> The source CSV contains two completely separate experiments laid out side-by-side
> in the same sheet. The left block (~263 chill hours, 15-Jan assessment) occupies
> columns 1–10, and the right block (~200 chill hours, 3-Jan assessment) occupies
> columns 12–21. The genotype in column 1 and the genotype in column 12 are
> **different plants on every row** — they happen to share a row only because of
> how the Excel file was laid out.
>
> The original script derived `NAME` from the left `Lug Order` (col 1) but read
> `Total Buds` and `3-Jan` counts from the right-side columns (cols 14 & 16),
> silently attributing another plant's phenotype to the wrong genotype on 937/940 rows.
>
> **Fix:** Parse the two blocks as separate data frames, assign each its own NAME,
> and derive all traits within each block before joining on NAME.

```{r load-reshape}
ph_raw <- .read_csv(pheno_file)
names(ph_raw) <- make.unique(names(ph_raw))  # handles duplicate Excel headers safely

# ── Left block: ~263 chill hours, assessed 15-Jan ──────────────────────────
# Columns: Lug Order | Position | Date of 1st Budbreak | Total Buds | 1-Jan | 15-Jan ...
left_block <- ph_raw %>%
  select(
    LugOrder  = `Lug Order`,
    TotalBuds = `Total Buds`,
    Cnt_15Jan = `15-Jan`
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(LugOrder), LugOrder != "") %>%
  mutate(
    NAME      = get_name(LugOrder),
    # FIX (was): Lug fixed effect used full LugOrder string (all unique) — saturated model.
    # Extract spatial block letter (A/B/C/D) from lug ID for use in BLUP/BLUE models.
    Block     = stringr::str_extract(LugOrder, "[A-Da-d](?=_\\d+$)"),
    TotalBuds = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(TotalBuds)),
    Cnt_15Jan = .clamp_counts(Cnt_15Jan, TotalBuds)
  ) %>%
  # FIX (was): zero or missing Total Buds caused silent NaN in FRAC/PERCENT columns
  filter(!is.na(TotalBuds), TotalBuds > 0) %>%
  mutate(
    PERCENT_15Jan = 100 * Cnt_15Jan / TotalBuds,
    FRAC_15Jan    = Cnt_15Jan / TotalBuds,
    BIN_15Jan     = as.integer(Cnt_15Jan > 0)
  )

# ── Right block: ~200 chill hours, assessed 3-Jan ──────────────────────────
# make.unique renames duplicated headers: second "Lug Order" → "Lug Order.1",
# second "Total Buds" → "Total Buds.1"
right_block <- ph_raw %>%
  select(
    LugOrder  = `Lug Order.1`,
    TotalBuds = `Total Buds.1`,
    Cnt_3Jan  = `3-Jan`
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(LugOrder), LugOrder != "") %>%
  mutate(
    NAME      = get_name(LugOrder),
    Block     = stringr::str_extract(LugOrder, "[A-Da-d](?=_\\d+$)"),
    TotalBuds = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(TotalBuds)),
    Cnt_3Jan  = .clamp_counts(Cnt_3Jan, TotalBuds)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(TotalBuds), TotalBuds > 0) %>%
  mutate(
    PERCENT_3Jan = 100 * Cnt_3Jan / TotalBuds,
    FRAC_3Jan    = Cnt_3Jan / TotalBuds,
    BIN_3Jan     = as.integer(Cnt_3Jan > 0)
  )

cat("[RESHAPE] Left block rows :", nrow(left_block),
    "| Unique genotypes:", n_distinct(left_block$NAME), "\n")
cat("[RESHAPE] Right block rows:", nrow(right_block),
    "| Unique genotypes:", n_distinct(right_block$NAME), "\n")
```

## PF Assignment

```{r pf-assignment}
all_names <- union(unique(left_block$NAME), unique(right_block$NAME))

# FIX (was): Named commercial varieties fell through to PF=NA, causing them to
# be silently dropped from FF-only cohort runs instead of being explicitly excluded
# or classified. Now all known varieties are explicitly assigned.
PF_tbl <- tibble(NAME = all_names) %>%
  mutate(
    PF = case_when(
      # Breeding lines — determined by name prefix
      startsWith(NAME, "APF")   ~ 1L,   # primocane-fruiting advanced lines
      startsWith(NAME, "A-")    ~ 0L,   # floricane-fruiting advanced lines
      # Named commercial varieties — classified by known biology
      NAME %in% c(
        "PrimeArkFreedom",
        "PrimeArkHorizon",
        "Superlicious"
      )                         ~ 1L,   # confirmed PF commercial varieties
      NAME %in% c(
        "Osage", "Ouachita", "Natchez",
        "Apache", "Ponca", "Caddo",
        "Navaho", "Lochness", "Immaculate",
        "Von", "Tupy", "Stella"
      )                         ~ 0L,   # confirmed FF commercial varieties
      TRUE                      ~ NA_integer_  # unknown — review if any appear below
    )
  )

cat("[PF] PF=1:", sum(PF_tbl$PF == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    "| PF=0:", sum(PF_tbl$PF == 0, na.rm = TRUE),
    "| PF=NA:", sum(is.na(PF_tbl$PF)), "\n")

# Print any names that fell through to NA so you can classify them manually
na_names <- PF_tbl %>% filter(is.na(PF)) %>% pull(NAME)
if (length(na_names) > 0) {
  cat("[PF WARNING] Unclassified genotypes (PF=NA) — add to case_when above:\n")
  print(na_names)
}
```

## BLUP / BLUE Models

> **FIX (was): The BLUP model used `factor(Lug Order)` as a fixed effect, where
> every Lug Order string is a unique individual ID (940 rows, 940 unique values).
> This completely saturated the fixed-effect matrix, leaving no residual variance
> for `(1|NAME)` to estimate — resulting in singular models and meaningless BLUPs.**
>
> **Fix:** Extract the spatial block letter (A/B/C/D) from the lug ID string and
> use that as the environmental covariate. This correctly partitions within-block
> spatial variation from genotype random effects.

```{r blup-blue}
mk_blup_blue <- function(df, trait) {

  message("[BLUP/BLUE] Processing: ", trait)

  df <- df %>%
    filter(!is.na(.data[[trait]]), is.finite(.data[[trait]]))

  if (nrow(df) < 10 || n_distinct(df$NAME) < 3) {
    message("[SKIP] Not enough data for ", trait)
    fallback <- df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(
        !!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
        !!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
        .groups = "drop"
      )
    return(list(
      BLUP = fallback %>% select(NAME, paste0("BLUP_", trait)),
      BLUE = fallback %>% select(NAME, paste0("BLUE_", trait))
    ))
  }

  df$NAME  <- factor(df$NAME)
  df$Block <- factor(df$Block)  # spatial block letter A/B/C/D extracted from lug ID

  # ── BLUP ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  blups_tbl <- tryCatch({
    m1 <- lmer(
      as.formula(paste0(trait, " ~ Block + (1|NAME)")),
      data    = df,
      REML    = TRUE,
      control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa",
                            optCtrl   = list(maxfun = 1e5))
    )
    re <- ranef(m1)$NAME
    tibble(
      NAME                      = rownames(re),
      !!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := as.numeric(re[, "(Intercept)"])
    )
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("[BLUP FAIL] Using genotype means for ", trait, " — ", conditionMessage(e))
    df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(!!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
                .groups = "drop")
  })

  # ── BLUE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  blues_tbl <- tryCatch({
    m2  <- lm(as.formula(paste0(trait, " ~ Block + NAME")), df)
    co  <- coef(m2)
    val <- co[grepl("^NAME", names(co))]
    tibble(
      NAME                      = gsub("^NAME", "", names(val)),
      !!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := as.numeric(val)
    )
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("[BLUE FAIL] Using genotype means for ", trait, " — ", conditionMessage(e))
    df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(!!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
                .groups = "drop")
  })

  list(BLUP = blups_tbl, BLUE = blues_tbl)
}

bb3  <- mk_blup_blue(right_block, "PERCENT_3Jan")
bb15 <- mk_blup_blue(left_block,  "PERCENT_15Jan")
```

## Composite Traits

```{r composite-traits}
# FIX (was): COMP traits previously averaged across rows where each row's two
# timepoints came from different genotypes (cross-contamination issue). Now that
# each block is correctly separated, we join by NAME before averaging, so COMP
# is a true within-genotype summary across chill-hour treatments.
left_means <- left_block %>%
  group_by(NAME) %>%
  summarise(across(c(BIN_15Jan, FRAC_15Jan, PERCENT_15Jan),
                   \(x) mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)),
            .groups = "drop")

right_means <- right_block %>%
  group_by(NAME) %>%
  summarise(across(c(BIN_3Jan, FRAC_3Jan, PERCENT_3Jan),
                   \(x) mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)),
            .groups = "drop")

COMP_tbl <- full_join(left_means, right_means, by = "NAME") %>%
  mutate(
    COMP_PERCENT = rowMeans(cbind(PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan), na.rm = TRUE),
    COMP_FRAC    = rowMeans(cbind(FRAC_3Jan,    FRAC_15Jan),    na.rm = TRUE)
  )
```

## Phenotypic PCA (PC1 & PC2 traits)

> **PCA NOTE — What this is and why we compute it:**
> Runs 13, 14, 27, 28, 41, and 42 use PC1 and PC2 as the GWAS traits rather than
> the raw/transformed budbreak measurements. The goal is to capture the major axes
> of phenotypic covariation across all budbreak traits in a single composite score,
> which can reveal genomic signals that are diluted when each individual trait is
> tested separately.
>
> **This is a phenotypic PCA, not a genomic one.** It is run on the matrix of
> per-genotype mean budbreak traits (PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan, FRAC_3Jan,
> FRAC_15Jan) after scaling each trait to unit variance. Population structure
> correction is still handled downstream by GWASpoly's kinship matrix (set.K),
> not by these PC scores.
>
> **Interpreting the PCs:**
> - **PC1** typically captures overall budbreak responsiveness — genotypes that
>   broke more buds at both timepoints score high; low-responders score low.
> - **PC2** typically captures the contrast between early (3-Jan) and late
>   (15-Jan) budbreak — genotypes that burst quickly vs. those that spread
>   budbreak across the assessment window.
>
> **Variance explained** is printed below — if PC1 explains <50% of variance,
> interpret PC2 results cautiously as there may not be a clean biological axis.

```{r pca-phenotypic}
# Build a wide matrix of per-genotype mean traits for PCA input
pca_input <- COMP_tbl %>%
  select(NAME, PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan, FRAC_3Jan, FRAC_15Jan) %>%
  filter(complete.cases(.))  # prcomp requires no missing values

pca_mat <- pca_input %>%
  select(-NAME) %>%
  scale()  # center and scale each trait to unit variance before PCA

# Run PCA using base R prcomp — no additional packages needed
# scale.=FALSE because the matrix is already scaled above
pca_res <- prcomp(pca_mat, center = FALSE, scale. = FALSE)

# Extract PC1 and PC2 scores and attach genotype names
pca_scores <- tibble(
  NAME = pca_input$NAME,
  PC1  = pca_res$x[, 1],
  PC2  = pca_res$x[, 2]
)

var_exp <- summary(pca_res)$importance["Proportion of Variance", ]
cat("[PCA] PC1 variance explained:", round(var_exp[1] * 100, 1), "%\n")
cat("[PCA] PC2 variance explained:", round(var_exp[2] * 100, 1), "%\n")
cat("[PCA] Genotypes included    :", nrow(pca_scores), "\n")
```

